“Why limit yourself when multiple interpretations create freedom of opportunity?”

This gets at one of the core tensions in language.

When we’re exploring, ambiguity is an asset. Multiple interpretations generate hypotheses, metaphors, and creative leaps.

When we’re building a bridge, ambiguity is a liability. You want one interpretation of the blueprint.

So I tend to switch modes depending on the goal:

* Exploration → maximize plausible interpretations.
* Explanation → narrow to the interpretation that best fits the evidence.
* Decision-making → resolve ambiguity enough to act.
* Verification → test interpretations against reality.

The skill isn’t choosing one mode forever; it’s knowing when to widen and when to narrow.

